### 1. One-Line Summary
* Rozena is the more forgiving, easier, and lower-risk rubber; Tenergy 80 is the higher-ceiling, more dangerous, and more demanding rubber. Butterflys current published indices also place Tenergy 80 slightly above Rozena in speed, spin, arc, and sponge hardness: Tenergy 80 (85 / 73 / 77 / 36) vs Rozena (83 / 70 / 75 / 35).

### 2. Head-to-Head Breakdown
* **Speed & Gears:**
    * **Low Impact:** Rozena is calmer and easier at 60–80% effort. It gives cleaner depth control on compact strokes and is less jumpy when your timing is a little off. Butterfly explicitly positions Rozena around high tolerance and compensation for delicate errors.
    * **Top End:** Tenergy 80 clearly wins. When you engage the sponge hard, it carries more pace and a heavier ball through topspin-to-topspin exchanges. Its official speed index is higher.
    * **Linearity:** Rozena feels more linear and predictable; Tenergy 80 has more extra kick when you accelerate hard. That makes Rozena easier to trust, while Tenergy 80 rewards better technique more.

* **Spin Mechanics:**
    * **Opening Loop:** Tenergy 80 is stronger for quality first attack, especially when you brush and engage forward with conviction. It produces a heavier opening ball, though Rozena is easier to land consistently. Tenergy 80 also carries the higher official spin value.
    * **Max Spin:** Tenergy 80 wins. Its ceiling is noticeably higher on full forehand and backhand topspin, especially from mid-distance or in counterloop exchanges.
    * **Topsheet Grip:** Both are grippy Spring Sponge / High Tension rubbers, but Tenergy 80s topsheet-sponge interaction feels more bitey under strong engagement. Rozena grips well, yet it is tuned more for tolerance than maximum bite.

* **Flight Path (Throw Angle):**
    * **Arc Height:** Tenergy 80 throws a little higher and more aggressively. Butterflys published arc values support that: 77 for Tenergy 80 vs 75 for Rozena.
    * **Safety:** In real play, Rozena often feels safer for most intermediate players because the rebound is easier to manage, even though Tenergy 80 has the slightly higher official arc. Rozenas forgiveness helps when contact quality is inconsistent.

* **Feel & Feedback:**
    * **Sensation:** Rozena feels slightly softer, quieter, and more muted; Tenergy 80 feels crisper, more elastic, and more lively. Butterflys listed sponge hardness is 35 for Rozena and 36 for Tenergy 80, which matches that on-table impression.
    * **Dwell:** Rozena gives a slightly easier holding sensation at moderate impact; Tenergy 80 feels more dynamic and rewarding when you compress it properly. On clean contact, Tenergy 80 gives richer information, but it also exposes technical mistakes more clearly.

* **Control & Short Game:**
    * **Sensitivity:** Rozena is less reactive to incoming spin and less demanding in serve receive, push, and short touch. Tenergy 80 is still balanced by Tenergy standards, but it is more sensitive and asks for a cleaner racket angle. Butterfly also describes Rozena around tolerance and Tenergy 80 around highest-level balance of spin and speed.
    * **Touch Play:** Rozena is easier for drop shots, short pushes, and keeping the ball low without accidental pop-up. Tenergy 80 can absolutely do this, but it punishes lazy hands more.

* **Blocking & Countering:**
    * **Passive Block:** Rozena is better for pure passive stability. It absorbs a bit more and is easier to keep on the table when you are late or under pressure.
    * **Active Counter:** Tenergy 80 is better once you close the angle and punch through the ball. It was designed for balanced topspin, attack, and counterattack, and that shows in fast backhand counters and compact re-loops.

### 3. The Recommendation
* **Choose Rozena if:**
    * You want 75–85% of the Tenergy family feel with better forgiveness.
    * You are an improving intermediate to advanced club player who values consistency more than absolute ceiling.
    * You rely on compact strokes, close-to-table play, controlled backhand exchanges, and a safer short game.
    * You sometimes find Tenergy-class rubbers too lively, too spin-sensitive, or too demanding on off-days.

* **Choose Tenergy 80 if:**
    * You have solid technique and can consistently engage the sponge with quality timing.
    * You want a true high-end offensive rubber with better balance than Tenergy 05 and more spin bite than Tenergy 64.
    * You win points through aggressive topspin, countering, and transition play rather than pure containment.
    * You accept lower forgiveness in exchange for more speed, more spin, and a higher finishing ceiling.
